ğŸ“Œ HTTP Overview

HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) is the protocol used for communication between clients (e.g., browsers, APIs) and servers. It follows a requestâ€“response model.

HTTP is stateless â€” each request is independent; sessions (state) are implemented with cookies, tokens, etc.

HTTP evolves (HTTP/1.1 â†’ HTTP/2 â†’ HTTP/3) mostly in how messages are framed and optimized, but core semantics (methods, status codes) remain consistent.

Messages are composed of:

Start line (method or status),

Headers (metadata),

Body (optional content).

ğŸ§  HTTP Session Flow

(Summary of how a session/request works internally)

Client opens a connection (usually TCP) to server.

Client sends request with method + headers + optional body.

Server processes and sends response with status code + headers + optional body.

Connection may close or be reused (persistent connections, HTTP/2 multiplexing).

ğŸš€ Common HTTP Request Methods

HTTP methods define the intent of a request.

Method	Meaning	Safe	Idempotent
GET	Retrieve resource	Yes	Yes
HEAD	Same as GET, no body	Yes	Yes
POST	Create resource or process data	No	No
PUT	Replace/update resource	No	Yes
PATCH	Partially update resource	No	Not necessarily
DELETE	Remove resource	No	Yes
OPTIONS	Query supported methods	Yes	Yes
<!-- CONNECT/TRACE are less commonly used in typical REST APIs. --> :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

Notes:

Safe means it should not change server state (e.g., GET, HEAD).

Idempotent means multiple identical requests have the same server effect (useful in retries).

ğŸ§¾ HTTP Status Codes â€“ Important Ones to Remember

Status codes are grouped by their first digit and tell the client what happened with the request.

âœ… 1xx Informational

Rare in everyday use.

100 Continue â€“ server got initial headers, client can send body.

âœ… 2xx Success
Code	Meaning	Typical scenario
200 OK	Request succeeded	GET, POST success
201 Created	New resource created	POST/PUT creating resource
204 No Content	Successful, no body	DELETE success

2xx codes tell clients everything went well.

ğŸ”„ 3xx Redirection
Code	Meaning
301 Moved Permanently	Resource permanently at new URL
302 Found	Temporary redirect
304 Not Modified	Cached response still valid

â†’ Browser may automatically follow Location header.

ğŸš« 4xx Client Errors
Code	Meaning
400 Bad Request	Invalid client request
401 Unauthorized	Authentication required
403 Forbidden	Access not allowed
404 Not Found	Resource not found

â†’ These indicate issues with the request or client permissions.

âŒ 5xx Server Errors
Code	Meaning
500 Internal Server Error	Generic server failure
502 Bad Gateway	Invalid response from upstream
503 Service Unavailable	Server overloaded/maintenance

â†’ These indicate server problems.

ğŸ§  Quick Revision Cheat Sheet
Request Methods:

GET â€“ read

POST â€“ create/process

PUT â€“ update/replace

PATCH â€“ partial update

DELETE â€“ delete

HEAD/OPTIONS â€“ metadata & supported methods

Core Statuses:

200, 201, 204 â†’ Success

301, 302, 304 â†’ Redirection

400, 401, 403, 404 â†’ Client errors

500, 502, 503 â†’ Server errors

ğŸ“Œ Helpful Concepts

HTTP is stateless, but state can be managed on top (e.g., sessions/cookies).

The status line in a response includes version, status code, and reason phrase.

Headers help communicate control info (like caching, content type, etc.).

