ğŸŒ HTTP â€” Meaningful Revision Notes
1ï¸âƒ£ What is HTTP?

HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) is the foundation of data communication on the web.

It defines how clients (browser, mobile apps, APIs) communicate with servers

Uses a request â†’ response model

Runs on top of TCP/IP

Stateless by design â†’ each request is independent

Any â€œstateâ€ (login, cart, preferences) is handled outside HTTP using cookies, tokens, or sessions.

2ï¸âƒ£ Evolution of HTTP (Why versions matter)
ğŸ”¹ HTTP/0.9

Very simple

Only supported GET

No headers, no status codes

ğŸ”¹ HTTP/1.0

Introduced:

Headers

Status codes

Different HTTP methods

Still one request per connection (slow)

ğŸ”¹ HTTP/1.1 (still widely used)

Persistent connections (keep-alive)

Chunked transfer encoding

Better caching support

Still suffers from head-of-line blocking

ğŸ”¹ HTTP/2

Binary protocol (not text)

Multiplexing â†’ multiple requests over one connection

Header compression

Faster, more efficient

ğŸ”¹ HTTP/3

Built on QUIC (UDP) instead of TCP

Better performance on unstable networks

Avoids TCP connection delays

âš ï¸ Important:
Methods, status codes, and semantics stay the same across versions

3ï¸âƒ£ HTTP Messages (Request & Response structure)
ğŸ“¤ HTTP Request

A request contains:

Request line

GET /users HTTP/1.1


Headers

Metadata (content type, auth, caching)

Body (optional)

Used mainly with POST, PUT, PATCH

Example:

POST /login HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json

{ "username": "abc", "password": "xyz" }

ğŸ“¥ HTTP Response

A response contains:

Status line

HTTP/1.1 200 OK


Headers

Body (optional)

Example:

HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found
Content-Type: application/json

{ "error": "User not found" }

4ï¸âƒ£ HTTP Sessions & State Management

Since HTTP is stateless, sessions are managed using:

ğŸª Cookies

Stored in the browser

Automatically sent with each request

Can store:

Session ID

Preferences

Security flags:

HttpOnly

Secure

SameSite

ğŸ” Tokens (JWT, OAuth)

Sent explicitly via headers

Common in REST APIs

Stateless on server side

ğŸ§  Server-side sessions

Server stores session data

Client holds session ID

5ï¸âƒ£ HTTP Methods (Common & Practical)
Method	Purpose	Typical Use
GET	Fetch data	Read resource
POST	Submit data	Create resource
PUT	Replace resource	Full update
PATCH	Partial update	Update specific fields
DELETE	Remove resource	Delete
HEAD	Headers only	Check resource metadata
OPTIONS	Supported methods	CORS, preflight
Concepts to remember:

Safe â†’ Does not modify data (GET, HEAD)

Idempotent â†’ Same result if repeated (GET, PUT, DELETE)

POST is NOT idempotent

